<figureCitation id="DB33B674A60A5A8CB84AE71817282627" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Trichopolydesmus eremitis Verhoeff, 1898 A, D-F, I holotype ♂ (ZSM-A 20033529) B, H, J, K holotype ♂ (ZMB 13160) C ♂ (VMNH 110683) A microslide with habitus parts B microslide with gonopods and one lag pair C habitus, lateral view D collum, dorsal view E body rings 13 and 14, dorsal view F hypoproct, ventral view G telson, ventral view H leg? 7 I left legs 10 and 11 J, K? left gonopod, distomesal and distoanterolateral views, respectively. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (C), 0.1 mm (D-K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1097.83916.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/674283" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5B</figureCitation>
): gonopods, one leg pair (7?).
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AF8DCF1E4BCCECDADF4AB0327A160067" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="071081EBD66BFAEF3CE470D636B57FC7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Additional material.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="744241C86C394A4ECEE30055D5C21B12" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<specimenCount id="1434531733BB0B26E0D57C45E5F47422" type="male">1 ♂</specimenCount>
(VMNH110683), body in two pieces in alcohol (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4034D532BB046505C5DD95D87E1CEE93" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Trichopolydesmus eremitis Verhoeff, 1898 A, D-F, I holotype ♂ (ZSM-A 20033529) B, H, J, K holotype ♂ (ZMB 13160) C ♂ (VMNH 110683) A microslide with habitus parts B microslide with gonopods and one lag pair C habitus, lateral view D collum, dorsal view E body rings 13 and 14, dorsal view F hypoproct, ventral view G telson, ventral view H leg? 7 I left legs 10 and 11 J, K? left gonopod, distomesal and distoanterolateral views, respectively. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (C), 0.1 mm (D-K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1097.83916.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/674283" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5C</figureCitation>
), ring 7 and gonopods missing. For more details see below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CEDBFEDA2FF7D361E93885CD63837D97" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="50FAFAE5791FB713F32585C8FAFEEE13" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2AD4E07FEB6C2BCA457F8FA5325120A7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Known from several caves in the southern part of the Carpathians in Romania: 
<normalizedToken id="B32386EC9E8E48E3B9BFF44633C74694" originalValue="Peştera">Pestera</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="96B768017F5D983AFB315BBCD1934BE1" originalValue="Hoţilor">Hotilor</normalizedToken>
de la 
<normalizedToken id="518D69166C7EBD9CD7B3C71577DE07E8" originalValue="Băile">Băile</normalizedToken>
Herculane (type locality), 
<normalizedToken id="D91C6F65CE51EEB9906C13B0FA008F3F" originalValue="Peştera">Pestera</normalizedToken>
nr. 40 de la 
<normalizedToken id="4399DCB157D6320E8253D3F0BAA0AC29" originalValue="Ineleţ">Inelet</normalizedToken>
, 
<normalizedToken id="08FA29EC6A19D3693CF49D4E10465E92" originalValue="Peştera">Pestera</normalizedToken>
Cicioara, 
<normalizedToken id="E652B91018E6AF1130168F146E48340E" originalValue="Peştera">Pestera</normalizedToken>
Cornetul 
<normalizedToken id="E0E8E7240BBE72D18B5E77DBF3C0092C" originalValue="Vârcanilor">Varcanilor</normalizedToken>
, 
<normalizedToken id="5BDCD39C0D5DDA5D744BF00DCD6ECFC5" originalValue="Peştera">Pestera</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="103F06885B6B5AE428227808CAB1082C" originalValue="Cloşani">Closani</normalizedToken>
, 
<normalizedToken id="FCEA1B44AEFEA7C2F8A528B6A112B55A" originalValue="Peştera">Pestera</normalizedToken>
Vacilor de la 
<normalizedToken id="1080D9958622F8A053B1CDA69CE7B67B" originalValue="Cloşani">Closani</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken id="6559B3736D8EFF7B2F1A4FF6E9249A83" originalValue="Peştera">Pestera</normalizedToken>
din Poiana Lazului (= 
<normalizedToken id="645471DEE9240B5A436031AD2B5C34A2" originalValue="Peştera">Pestera</normalizedToken>
lui Mihai Arjoc, = 
<normalizedToken id="08CCF78820FCEAB079167943EC7872C9" originalValue="Peştera">Pestera</normalizedToken>
din Piatra 
<normalizedToken id="CD1A642AA80DBEAFCE1ED57E29C4398B" originalValue="Mică">Mică</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="64167BAB372A8F88D99A04F56B3A6947" author="Verhoeff, KW" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="363 - 372" refId="B64" refString="Verhoeff, KW, 1898. Beitraege zur Kenntniss palaearktischer Myriopoden. VII. Aufsatz: Ueber neue und wenig bekannte Polydesmiden aus Siebenbuergen, Rumaenien und dem Banat. Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte 64 (1): 363 - 372" title="Beitraege zur Kenntniss palaearktischer Myriopoden. VII. Aufsatz: Ueber neue und wenig bekannte Polydesmiden aus Siebenbuergen, Rumaenien und dem Banat." volume="64" year="1898">Verhoeff 1898</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="CAC6FF904C541B33B667041CA6481739" author="Ceuca, T" journalOrPublisher="Studii si Cercetări de Biologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="335 - 343" refId="B14" refString="Ceuca, T, 1958. Contributii la cunoasterea Diplopodelor din fauna R. P. Romine. III. Diplopode cavernicole. Studii si Cercetări de Biologie 2: 335 - 343" title="Contributii la cunoasterea Diplopodelor din fauna R. P. Romine. III. Diplopode cavernicole." volume="2" year="1958">Ceuca 1958</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="3020059F6F2A021A897DF89E1C966D52" author="Tabacaru, I" journalOrPublisher="Travaux de l'Institut de Speologie &quot; Emile Racovitza &quot;" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B60" refString="Tabacaru, I, Giurginca, A, Vanoaica, L, 2003. Cavernicolous Diplopoda of Romania. Travaux de l'Institut de Speologie &quot;Emile Racovitza&quot; 41-42: 121-148." title="Cavernicolous Diplopoda of Romania. Travaux de l'Institut de Speologie &quot; Emile Racovitza &quot; 41 - 42: 121 - 148." year="2003">Tabacaru et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4BA0AA5F44F4A58638E5507782AF257E" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Distribution of cavernicolous Trichopolydesmidae from the Carpathian-Balkan arch and the Rhodope Mountains." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1097.83916.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/674296" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">18</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5DB93CB90FE8477F64C5E88E52651D0B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="A0EBE10468810E5DD9453297C4735148" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F538BD4181D618D5E23C4EEF9618E66B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<bibRefCitation id="F72DC0306DB8D8944B96555352188CCC" author="Verhoeff, KW" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="363 - 372" refId="B64" refString="Verhoeff, KW, 1898. Beitraege zur Kenntniss palaearktischer Myriopoden. VII. Aufsatz: Ueber neue und wenig bekannte Polydesmiden aus Siebenbuergen, Rumaenien und dem Banat. Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte 64 (1): 363 - 372" title="Beitraege zur Kenntniss palaearktischer Myriopoden. VII. Aufsatz: Ueber neue und wenig bekannte Polydesmiden aus Siebenbuergen, Rumaenien und dem Banat." volume="64" year="1898">Verhoeff (1898)</bibRefCitation>
described this taxon from a single male he collected in the 
<normalizedToken id="7C708FD688B21712C100F1E77533531A" originalValue="Hoţilor">Hotilor</normalizedToken>
Cave in 
<normalizedToken id="4406C99542A35C12020EEC6B3F18D122" originalValue="Băile">Băile</normalizedToken>
Herculane. As he himself stated, several subsequent attempts to collect additional specimens in this cave were unsuccessful. 
<bibRefCitation id="E0F9D941E49DE7A19A73CF6A97C93AE9" author="Tabacaru, I" journalOrPublisher="Travaux de l'Institut de Speologie &quot; Emile Racovitza &quot;" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="155 - 161" refId="B58" refString="Tabacaru, I, 1980. Trichopolydesmus (Banatodesmus) jeanneli n. sg., n. sp. Travaux de l'Institut de Speologie &quot;Emile Racovitza&quot; 24: 155 - 161" title="Trichopolydesmus (Banatodesmus) jeanneli n. sg., n. sp." volume="24" year="1980">Tabacaru (1980)</bibRefCitation>
stated that numerous searches in this cave failed too. One of us (DA) visited this cave in 2014 but also failed to find this species. In 2021, a small group of myriapodologists, including two of us (DA and BV) were not successful either. From 
<normalizedToken id="E2C101258D20C29FC3189D0A3EAA9BC1" originalValue="Hoţilor">Hotilor</normalizedToken>
Cave, only the male type specimen originally described by 
<bibRefCitation id="2957837FCCAD1304B46CF897C61BDCCC" author="Verhoeff, KW" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="363 - 372" refId="B64" refString="Verhoeff, KW, 1898. Beitraege zur Kenntniss palaearktischer Myriopoden. VII. Aufsatz: Ueber neue und wenig bekannte Polydesmiden aus Siebenbuergen, Rumaenien und dem Banat. Archiv fuer Naturgeschichte 64 (1): 363 - 372" title="Beitraege zur Kenntniss palaearktischer Myriopoden. VII. Aufsatz: Ueber neue und wenig bekannte Polydesmiden aus Siebenbuergen, Rumaenien und dem Banat." volume="64" year="1898">Verhoeff (1898)</bibRefCitation>
is known.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D131D9FB1A6A6381BB8DAE8483BB4BB3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Sixty years after its original description, 
<bibRefCitation id="B64D0856ACCF835D5EEC1E49D8C99B25" author="Ceuca, T" journalOrPublisher="Studii si Cercetări de Biologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="335 - 343" refId="B14" refString="Ceuca, T, 1958. Contributii la cunoasterea Diplopodelor din fauna R. P. Romine. III. Diplopode cavernicole. Studii si Cercetări de Biologie 2: 335 - 343" title="Contributii la cunoasterea Diplopodelor din fauna R. P. Romine. III. Diplopode cavernicole." volume="2" year="1958">Ceuca (1958)</bibRefCitation>
examined more than 20 specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="6381FA3D981E80265D39F4EC2E8DB6BF" class="Diplopoda" genus="T." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="T. eremitis" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eremitis">
<emphasis id="0E66CE6975E7FE7440DC2246F1C48ACD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">T. eremitis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from three other caves and gave new and more detailed drawings of the gonopods (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A7FEE4CB89EAFDD137B6342907CE5125" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Gonopods of cavernicolous Trichopolydesmidae from the Carpathian-Balkan arch and Rhodopes A-C Bacillidesmus filiformis (Latzel, 1884) lectotype ♂ (NHWM MY 3754) A after Attems (1898) B? left gonopod,? mesal view, after Attems (1940) C? left gonopod,? mesal view, present study D Banatodesmus jeanneli (Tabacaru, 1980) syntype ♂, right gonopod, mesal view, after Tabacaru (1980) E, F Napocodesmus florentzae Tabacaru, 1975 holotype ♂, right gonopod, mesal and anterior views, respectively, after Tabacaru (1975) G, H Trichopolydesmus eremitis Verhoeff, 1898 ♂ from Closani cave, right gonopod, antero-mesal and mesal views, respectively, after Ceuca (1958) I Balkanodesminus bulgaricus (Strasser, 1962) gen. nov., comb. nov. ♂ from Ponora Cave (NMNHS- 10813), left gonopod, mesal view J Balkanodesminus serbicus gen. nov. et sp. nov. paratype ♂ (NHMW MY 10263), left gonopod, mesal view K Rhodopodesmus niveus gen. nov. et sp. nov. holotype ♂ (NMNHS- 10823), left gonopod, mesal view L Balkanodesminus dentatus (Strasser, 1966 a) gen. nov., comb. nov., stat. nov. syntype ♂, right gonopod, mesal view, after Strasser (1966 a) M Balkanodesminus dentatoides gen. nov. et sp. nov. paratype ♂ (NHMW MY 10258), right gonopod, mesal view N Balkanodesminus dentatoides gen. nov. et sp. nov. ♂ from Sopotska Cave (NHMW MY 10267), left gonopod, mesal view. Scale bars: 0.05 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1097.83916.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/674295" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">17G, H</figureCitation>
), as well as some notes on female habitus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C8460EDF24BDFB57D36A8669CE735FF2" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<bibRefCitation id="C4F06DC881F539DF4FE6616973CB2329" author="Hoffman, RL" journalOrPublisher="Museum d'Histoire naturelle, Geneve, 1979" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B31" refString="Hoffman, RL, 1980. Classification of Diplopoda. Museum d'Histoire naturelle, Geneve, 1979" title="Classification of Diplopoda." year="1980">Hoffman (1980)</bibRefCitation>
wrote that he had received a male from Traian Ceuca, whose photograph is included in this paper (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DDF757E3C09D4CFE4AB3D1F5E0F12384" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Trichopolydesmus eremitis Verhoeff, 1898 A, D-F, I holotype ♂ (ZSM-A 20033529) B, H, J, K holotype ♂ (ZMB 13160) C ♂ (VMNH 110683) A microslide with habitus parts B microslide with gonopods and one lag pair C habitus, lateral view D collum, dorsal view E body rings 13 and 14, dorsal view F hypoproct, ventral view G telson, ventral view H leg? 7 I left legs 10 and 11 J, K? left gonopod, distomesal and distoanterolateral views, respectively. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (C), 0.1 mm (D-K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1097.83916.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/674283" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5C</figureCitation>
). Unfortunately, colleague Jackson Means informed us that there is no original label with this individual, but that on the jar, marked with MIR02733, it is written: &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="2AE740A0BDA0D3613394E3B7CE66AD86" authorityName="Verhoeff" authorityYear="1910" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopolydesmidae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Trichopolydesmidae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName id="B5F7679C34E33BAC2EF3762975D7410D" authorityName="Verhoeff" authorityYear="1898" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopolydesmidae" genus="Trichopolydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trichopolydesmus eremitis" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eremitis">
<emphasis id="1CB19F9FF0707F46D6266C967B70686A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Trichopolydesmus eremitis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Verhoeff TOPOTYPES !! Hungary&quot;. This was probably an accidental mistake during the subsequent labeling. The male sent by Ceuca to Hoffman comes from one of the three caves in Romania listed in 
<bibRefCitation id="A8BEEE7A406D8F12F41F7561D3790F41" author="Ceuca, T" journalOrPublisher="Studii si Cercetări de Biologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="335 - 343" refId="B14" refString="Ceuca, T, 1958. Contributii la cunoasterea Diplopodelor din fauna R. P. Romine. III. Diplopode cavernicole. Studii si Cercetări de Biologie 2: 335 - 343" title="Contributii la cunoasterea Diplopodelor din fauna R. P. Romine. III. Diplopode cavernicole." volume="2" year="1958">
<normalizedToken id="305228A83F9A26EDB921C3AAE673D237" originalValue="Ceuca’s">Ceuca's</normalizedToken>
(1958)
</bibRefCitation>
paper. Considering the number of collected males from those three caves, we can only guess that this male comes from the 
<normalizedToken id="F15A0ECD9BB68855A86D0C6E8C6F9077" originalValue="Cloşani">Closani</normalizedToken>
cave.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D86A653199B041438EA7469AA139406C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Similarly to 
<taxonomicName id="1147F4D1DAAF811F9AC5BE82137C4A14" baseAuthorityName="Latzel" baseAuthorityYear="1884" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopolydesmidae" genus="Bacillidesmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bacillidesmus filiformis" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filiformis">
<emphasis id="666E0BF88CDC14FA0BFD0F5912D3753D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Bacillidesmus filiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this species also has ventral denticles on podomeres of male anterior legs (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2EAD2DE6E60AE20BF6159CA38BFB592A" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Trichopolydesmus eremitis Verhoeff, 1898 A, D-F, I holotype ♂ (ZSM-A 20033529) B, H, J, K holotype ♂ (ZMB 13160) C ♂ (VMNH 110683) A microslide with habitus parts B microslide with gonopods and one lag pair C habitus, lateral view D collum, dorsal view E body rings 13 and 14, dorsal view F hypoproct, ventral view G telson, ventral view H leg? 7 I left legs 10 and 11 J, K? left gonopod, distomesal and distoanterolateral views, respectively. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (C), 0.1 mm (D-K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1097.83916.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/674283" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5H, I</figureCitation>
). However, some other habitual characteristics are similar to 
<taxonomicName id="B3F36E71AA898C6291DB2DEE85C5330D" authorityName="Ceuca" authorityYear="1974" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopolydesmidae" genus="Napocodesmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Napocodesmus" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A229D1F1F7C19A00C53C3D6BD6F5A0D3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Napocodesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="6A0EEBB530FBDF6C4F53FDFD97787E30" authorityName="Antić &amp; Vagalinski &amp; Stoev &amp; Akkari" authorityYear="2022" family="Trichopolydesmidae" genus="Balkanodesminus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Balkanodesminus" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75F2A186F7CCD768E9FD23A78F2DD093" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Balkanodesminus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. nov. and 
<taxonomicName id="3214EB343B8E187AFDCD83E1CBB95947" authorityName="Antić &amp; Vagalinski &amp; Stoev &amp; Akkari" authorityYear="2022" family="Trichopolydesmidae" genus="Rhodopodesmus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhodopodesmus" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1DB3D373187445E8A08840C6C3ADB08F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Rhodopodesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. nov., viz., sensilla basiconica on antennomere 6 partially exposed outside the pit, while hypoproct and paraprocts are with more than two long setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CF1B4B3BD859EABB9A053843C737ED6D" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Trichopolydesmus eremitis Verhoeff, 1898 A, D-F, I holotype ♂ (ZSM-A 20033529) B, H, J, K holotype ♂ (ZMB 13160) C ♂ (VMNH 110683) A microslide with habitus parts B microslide with gonopods and one lag pair C habitus, lateral view D collum, dorsal view E body rings 13 and 14, dorsal view F hypoproct, ventral view G telson, ventral view H leg? 7 I left legs 10 and 11 J, K? left gonopod, distomesal and distoanterolateral views, respectively. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (C), 0.1 mm (D-K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1097.83916.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/674283" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5F, G</figureCitation>
). Legs and antennomeres (as well as antennae in general) in this species are somewhat longer (slender) than in other representatives from the Carpathian-Balkan arch and the Rhodope Mountains, thus it seems to be the most strongly adapted to cave life among them.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
